description:
lib.rs:327-342: two inventory::submit! invocations that differ only in (a) the registration type (BackendRegistration vs WritableBackendRegistration) and (b) the trait object cast in the closure body.

```rust
inventory::submit!(secretx_core::BackendRegistration {
    name: "vault",
    factory: |uri: &str| {
        VaultBackend::from_uri(uri)
            .map(|b| std::sync::Arc::new(b) as std::sync::Arc<dyn secretx_core::SecretStore>)
    },
});
inventory::submit!(secretx_core::WritableBackendRegistration {
    name: "vault",
    factory: |uri: &str| {
        VaultBackend::from_uri(uri).map(|b| {
            std::sync::Arc::new(b) as std::sync::Arc<dyn secretx_core::WritableSecretStore>
        })
    },
});
```

A macro could collapse the two — but only across all backends. The duplication is fine here because:
1. Only writable backends register both; read-only backends only register the first.
2. The trait object casts differ in target type and cannot share a single closure.
3. Macro abstraction would obscure the registration mechanism, which is currently grep-able.

Filing as P4/opinion to record that I considered it and declined. Defend against: 'DRY this up' — DRY here would be net-negative abstraction.
